Microalgae constitute a functionally, physiologically and ecologically diverse group endowed with a great wealth of bioactive compounds (

; Sasso et al., 2012), playing significant roles in the balance and operation of the planet's ecosystems (

; 

). Along with this biochemical diversity, many eukaryotic microalgae offer several advantages for the molecular farming of bioactive compounds, including fast growth rate, ease of cultivation, autotrophy, and capacity to grow in bioreactors (

; Ruffing, 2011). One of the most widely used organisms is the chlorophyte 

Chlamydomonas reinhardtii

(
Chlamydomonadaceae
) (

; Rosales-Mendoza et al., 2011; Scaife et al., 2015), a model unicellular microalgal species, extensively characterized at molecular level (

; Gomes de Oliveira Dal’ Molin et al., 2011; 

; 

). Recombinant protein production has been achieved in this species by transformation of either the nucleus, the mitochondrion, or the chloroplast (

; 

; 

; Rosales-Mendoza et al., 2011; Scaife et al., 2015). 

Chlamydomonas

is considered a valuable industrial biotechnology platform (Scaife et al., 2015), especially for products from plants, with which it shares many of the essential and specialized biosynthetic pathways, including that leading to the synthesis of terpenoids (

; 

; Schwender et al., 2001).

Microalgae have been used for the heterologous production of isoprenoid compounds such as sterols, terpenoids and carotenoids (

; 

; 

; 

; 

; Vickers et al., 2014). Plants produce terpenoid compounds from isopentenyl diphosphate (IPP) and dimethylallyl pyrophosphate (DMAPP), synthesized both 
via
the cytoplasmic mevalonate (MVA) pathway, and 
via
the plastid methyl-D-erythritol 4-phosphate/1-deoxy-D-xylulose 5-phosphate (MEP/DXP) pathway (Tholl, 2015), while Chlorophyta, including 

C. reinhardtii

, employ exclusively the MEP/DXP pathway for the production of these metabolites (

; 

; Schwender et al., 2001). Heterologous production in 

C. reinhardtii

was achieved for the monoterpene limonene (Syrenne, 2016), and the sesquiterpenes patchulol (

) and 
α
-bisabolene (Wichmann et al., 2018). More recently, the genes of a cytochrome P450 enzyme (

) and the bifunctional 
cis
-abienol synthase (
AbCAS
) (Zedler et al., 2015), were expressed in 

C. reinhardtii

plastids. Another LD, the forskolin diterpenoid precursor 13R(+) manoyl oxide was produced in 

Chlamydomonas

by heterologous expression of a plant diterpenoid synthase (

).

